post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_27328876_27328876_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 611}}, "n3337": {"so_27328876_27328876_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 601}}, "n4659": {"so_27328876_27328876_0": {"length": 9, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 637}}}, "27329263": {"Id": "27329263", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The line you quoted is under the section titled <strong>13.3.3.1.1 Standard Conversion Sequences</strong>. The conversion from <code>B</code> to <code>A</code> is a user defined conversion. The rules for user defined conversions are under the next section of the standard and is titled <strong>13.3.3.1.2 User-defined conversion sequences</strong></p>\n<p>What you quoted does not apply to user defined conversions.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-12-06T07:08:14.030", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-12-06T07:08:14.030", "ParentId": "27328876", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "434551"}, "27328876": {"ViewCount": "27", "Body": "<p>I've written the example:</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nstruct A\n{\n    A(const A&amp;){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"A(const A&amp;)\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n    A(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"A()\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n};\n\nstruct B\n{\n    B(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"B()\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n    operator A(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"operator A()\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; return A(); }\n};\n\nB b;\n\nvoid foo(A) { }\n\nint main(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"main function starting...\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; foo(b); }\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://coliru.stacked-crooked.com/a/7f3dc20acbbd5704\" rel=\"nofollow\">DEMO</a></strong></p>\n<p>It works fine, but if we replace <code>B b;</code> with <code>const B b;</code> it won't work. </p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\n\nstruct A\n{\n    A(const A&amp;){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"A(const A&amp;)\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n    A(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"A()\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n};\n\nstruct B\n{\n    B(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"B()\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; }\n    operator A(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"operator A()\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; return A(); }\n};\n\nconst B b;\n\nvoid foo(A) { }\n\nint main(){ std::cout &lt;&lt; \"main function starting...\" &lt;&lt; std::endl; foo(b); }\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://coliru.stacked-crooked.com/a/dc9483315228fbb9\" rel=\"nofollow\">DEMO</a></strong></p>\n<p>Although the Standard says in the section <code>13.3.3.1/6 [over.best.ics]</code>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27328876_27328876_0\">Any difference in top-level cv-qualification is subsumed by the\n  initialization itself and does not constitute a conversion.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I wish someone to explain me why the seond example doesn't work.</p>\n", "Title": "A CV-qualified type cannot be converted to the cv-unqualified type", "CreationDate": "2014-12-06T06:08:24.210", "LastActivityDate": "2014-12-06T07:08:14.030", "CommentCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "OwnerDisplayName": "user2953119", "Id": "27328876", "Score": "0", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "1"}});